segments.text: Captain Wheeler, who weighed 300 pounds, he's the only guy I knew in the Army who had two pistol belts around him.
How'd they let him stay in?
They waved him.
In the guard you could do that.
He and I were freshmen at A&M, four years there.
After we worked all day in the field, we'd go to the officer club and have a few beers and we would have a ball.
We had a storm one night, one weekend.
And it was a tornado.
And we were out there holding ropes and holding tents.
And mess halls were flying all over the place.
And damn, Wheeler would, Sam, call me on the phone.
The phones were still intact for some reason.
The field phone said, hey, you got any privates you can send over to help hold the tent down?
I said, hell no.
I'm holding the tent down myself.
So after that weekend,
Monday night, we worked all day getting everything straight.
Monday, we worked all day getting everything straight.
And then Monday night, we were all tired and battered and beat.
And we went to the officer's club and had a few beers.
And next thing I knew, Sam Wheeler and I, Captain Wheeler and I, were in the middle of the officer's club dance floor imitating the generals.
Yeah.
And who walks in?
The generals.
That never fails.
And of course, everybody in the,
We knew everybody.
We knew everybody in the division.
And they walked in and we put on an act about the big win.
And we had apple crates on the floor like we were in the general's chair.
And we said, ah, well, what's the troops doing down in the field?
General Wheeler, Captain Wheeler said, well, the damn missile's blowing away.
Let them blow away.
We can get some, you know.
We made fun of them, see.
And we got through.
The damn officer club just roared.
Just laughed like hell.
And it all at once got quiet.
We looked around.
There was General Ainsworth and General Ives and General Simpson.
We didn't know what to do.
General Miller walked up, boy, and he clapped.
And he says, do it again for me.
So every time we'd go to summer camp with their guard, we had to put on that Big Win Act.
So, you know, we had a sense of humor.
I don't know where else we covered.
All the schools.
Oh yeah, I went to... You went to Communist Strategy School.
And I wanted to talk, I forgot to ask you about that.
Tell me about this Communist Strategy School.
This is a
About what, 1961 was it?
Yeah, that's right.
Went to Washington.
Went to the State Department.
State Department.
They had openings.
They had some quotas for reserve officers.
I went.
And it dealt with the communist countries.
And at that time, they knew the communists were trying to dominate the world.
And they wanted to make the military aware of it.
That's the purpose of it.
It spent two weeks there.
Very, very interesting.
And what did they talk about?
Did they talk about theory or Marxist theory?
Marxism.
Marxism.
Did they have people come in and talk to you?
Or did the State Department itself?
The State Department people came in and talked to us.
And they took each country in South America and told us...
gave us a background on how the Marxists was in there and how the communists was in there.
And then they got into European countries and they took each country.
And then they really didn't ever come up with a plan what they were doing to counteract it.
Did they know?
They really didn't know how to handle it.
And it was very interesting.
What was your opinion of the State Department personnel?
Wasn't top notch.
It wasn't?
No, it really wasn't.
They acted like they were in another government or something.
Really.
They held themselves aloof from us.
Just the outset, they were aloof.
I was very disappointed in them.
And then a book came out.
What was it?
Decisions on the fifth floor.
That's where the State Department decision made on the fifth floor of the state.
Yeah, and so I read excerpts of that and I can understand.
In fact, the guy that conducted the seminar talked with a British clip.
Yeah.
So I didn't feel like he was part of my government.
But yet he was...
Foreign service officer, career foreign service officer.
Maybe he was educated in England.
Maybe, you know.
Or maybe he had a lot of, maybe he had just got back from years of service in England or something like that.
And picked up some of that.
Picked up and really had a strong, but I never felt like they were part of us.
I really didn't.
I stood aloof.
I also went to the, I went to the nuclear...
a radiological nuclear damage course at Treasure Island when I was a captain.
I don't know why I went to that damn thing.
I was in the Guard.
I guess they had a quarter and wanted to send somebody, and I went there, and we went on these ships that they had at Utah.
I don't know, out in the Pacific where they were testing the nuclear bomb, the atom bombs.
And they had all these ships in there, and we had to get on them.
What year was this?
This is in 48.
It's not even on there.
No.
So this is in 48?
Yeah.
During the atomic test?
Yeah.
What's that island?
Those Antole Islands?
I went in there.
For some reason or another, I took a nuclear corresponding course.
I thought it was interesting.
Well, they call it the atomic test.
the course and I thought it was interesting and I took it and had a lot of math in it and I didn't like that.
And then there was a Navy commander out here in the reserve and he was taking the same course and so we studied together.
And then I got a letter saying that I was eligible to go to this nuclear defense course out at Treasure Island.
Would I be interested in going as an Army representative?
I said yeah.
Two weeks on Treasure Island.
It was good duty.
But you didn't witness an atomic blast yourself?
No, no.
All we did was went through the cyclotron out at Beverly, not Beverly, Berkeley.
We went through everything, and that was new, you know.
So I did some pretty good school.
I went to some good schools.
Good schools.
I went to the, not Sean either, doing World War II when it was in England and the division artillery was levied upon to send somebody to the mine damage school of Great Britain.
And that, the purpose of that was how to deactivate mines.
And Terry, they were
There were two people killed in the school in several mains.
So you know how I felt.
All we had was a bayonet and we probed the ground for the mines.
And then we also set the, we had to make up patterns for mines.
And we also had to detect the patterns.
And when we got in combat, we were supposed to, if we're going across minefield, I was to be called up as the expert and say, now the minefield is set this way, this,
This is the way we deactivate.
See?
Yeah.
Thank God I never had to do that.
Did you ever go to that school?
Oh, yeah, I went to the school.
But you were never called on to go?
Oh, I went through the minefields.
I don't know how I never got my arm blown off.
I was very cautious.
Oh, I was cautious.
Oh, yeah, I went to the school.
Oh, sure.
But you were never called upon to go and deactivate a minefield?
At school?
In combat?
No.
I was too busy forward observing.
Yeah, I was too busy directing artillery fire.
What did you think of the schools in general?
They were good.
Very good.
The Army schools are excellent schools.
Excellent.
What do you think the best one was?
War College?
War College.
Oh yeah, that's the top school.
Oh yeah.
I also went to the
counterinsurgency school at Fort Bragg.
Catherine went with me this time.
Yeah, it was a counterinsurgency.
That was the special forces school.
When was this, early in the 60s?
I was a colonel.
No, I was a lieutenant colonel.
So it must have been late 50s, early 60s.
And General Stilwell was a commandant.
And we, it was a seminar type thing.
We studied insurgency activities and how to, and also how, if you drop behind the lines, how to organize the indigent people and how to resist counter-revolution and stuff.
just what's going on in El Salvador.
I hope they don't call me back for that.
No.
So I went to some good schools.
I really did.
So I think this helped me along the way to become a general officer.
And I felt kind of rounded out in education.
To where I could hold my own with anybody.
I don't care who you are.
But I look back now, A&M taught me, I repeat it many times, self-discipline.
It's extraordinarily important.
It is.
And law and order.
You've got to be the law.
Papa taught me that.
Papa taught me to love America and obey the laws.
So it gave me respect for authority, respect for responsibility, people.
And I was very fortunate to have a daddy like that.
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
So all of us brothers.
I'm deeply grateful to A&M.
Great school.
And I don't see anything wrong in the way it's going now.
Now, you know, I had mentioned to you earlier about the Corps and maybe those ones that don't want to get in the Corps could go through the ROTC program.
on second thought, it wouldn't be right for the Corps.
It would kill the Corps.
It would hurt them.
Yeah, so I'm going to withdraw that statement.
Okay, well we didn't get it on tape anyway.
Didn't we?
I don't know if we did or not.
No, we were talking about it in the kitchen.
Yeah, I guess we were.
And if we did, then... Well, we can cross it out, yeah.
What else?
I'm done.
I mean, I have exhausted my questions, but is there anything else that you think that's part of my...
Well, it's that old training now.
Do you feel like we've gone in the right direction in your...
In the interview?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah, absolutely.
This ends our interview then.
Thanks a lot, General.
I really appreciate it.
Well, I thank you, Terry.
You've been very nice and kind.
